docs.abstract: The bloody shooting of Republican lawmakers by a Bernie Sanders supporter could prove to be an opportunity for the senator’s fans to consider their message.
docs.snippet: The bloody shooting of Republican lawmakers by a Bernie Sanders supporter could prove to be an opportunity for the senator’s fans to consider their message.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The most ardent supporters of Senator Bernie Sanders have long been outspoken about their anger toward Republicans — and in some cases toward Democrats. Their idol, the senator from Vermont, has called President Trump a “demagogue” and said recently that he was “perhaps the worst and most dangerous president in the history of our country.”

headline.print_headline: Shooting Tests Movement on the Left

docs.abstract: “What makes a dance queer?” was one of many questions considered at Explode! Queer Dance, a festival that brought together artists and academics.
docs.snippet: “What makes a dance queer?” was one of many questions considered at Explode! Queer Dance, a festival that brought together artists and academics.
docs.lead_paragraph: As audience members took their seats for the final performance of Explode! Queer Dance on Saturday night, the choreographer, performer and dance scholar Thomas F. DeFrantz roamed among us, collecting suggestions.

headline.main: What Can Queer and Dance Do for Each Other?
headline.print_headline: Watching a Conversation, Not a Competition, Between Men

docs.abstract: In James Ijames’s play “Kill Move Paradise,” four young black men try — and fail — to understand how and why they died.
docs.snippet: In James Ijames’s play “Kill Move Paradise,” four young black men try — and fail — to understand how and why they died.
docs.lead_paragraph: Many emotions vie for dominance among the young men living in limbo in “Kill Move Paradise,” the bleak and beautiful new drama by James Ijames at the National Black Theater in Harlem. Fear, rage, disgust, helplessness, a sardonic amusement and a sorrow beyond tears — these responses ebb and flow in a seemingly unending cycle during the show’s time-bending 80 minutes.

headline.main: Review: The Unspeakable Pain of an African-American Afterlife
headline.print_headline: Bewildered Rage Over Lives Cut Short

docs.abstract: Mr. Maher and his guest, Senator Ben Sasse, Republican of Nebraska, were swiftly criticized on social media after Mr. Maher’s comments were broadcast.
docs.snippet: Mr. Maher and his guest, Senator Ben Sasse, Republican of Nebraska, were swiftly criticized on social media after Mr. Maher’s comments were broadcast.
docs.lead_paragraph: The HBO late-night host Bill Maher apologized on Saturday for using a racial epithet during an interview with Senator Ben Sasse, Republican of Nebraska, on a live broadcast of his show on Friday night. HBO denounced the remark as “completely inexcusable and tasteless,” and said it would be edited out of future airings.

headline.main: Bill Maher Apologizes for Use of Racial Slur on ‘Real Time’
headline.print_headline: Maher Apologizes for Use of Racial Slur on ‘Real Time’

docs.abstract: An anthology series based on hip-hop songs is an audacious idea, but the voice goes missing.
docs.snippet: An anthology series based on hip-hop songs is an audacious idea, but the voice goes missing.
docs.lead_paragraph: Years ago, Chuck D of the group Public Enemy called rap “the black CNN.” Now “Tales,” an anthology series beginning Tuesday on BET, asks if rap can also be HBO — a font of stories instead of headlines.

headline.main: Review: In BET’s ‘Tales,’ Rap Lyrics Get Lost in Translation

headline.main: He Sued Police 75 Times. Democrats Want Him as Philadelphia’s Top Prosecutor.

docs.abstract: The hard-right fringe is billing itself as today’s “punk rock” counterculture — even as it gleefully seizes power and influence over the mainstream.
docs.snippet: The hard-right fringe is billing itself as today’s “punk rock” counterculture — even as it gleefully seizes power and influence over the mainstream.
docs.lead_paragraph: An always-useful thought experiment is to imagine seeing all the media around you for the first time — consciously, like a teenager freshly awakened to the existence of politics or an artificial intelligence that has just blinked across some humanoid threshold. This is especially handy lately, in our strange moment of flux. A wide-​eyed observer of today’s political media wouldn’t just see different voices and outlets with contrasting tendencies. It would see a disorienting game of rhetorical appropriation, in which it is constantly unclear who stands for which principles and why.

headline.main: Why the Far Right Wants to Be the New ‘Alternative’ Culture

docs.abstract: The W.N.B.A. franchise, one of the few professional teams owned by women, will donate part of the proceeds from a July home game against the Chicago Sky to a chapter of the organization.
docs.snippet: The W.N.B.A. franchise, one of the few professional teams owned by women, will donate part of the proceeds from a July home game against the Chicago Sky to a chapter of the organization.
docs.lead_paragraph: Professional sports teams work with other businesses and organizations all the time. But the W.N.B.A.’s Seattle Storm announced on Thursday that they were wading into the current political climate in a way that contrasts with the practices of many other sports teams: a partnership with Planned Parenthood.

headline.main: Seattle Storm Take Progressive Tack With Planned Parenthood Partnership
headline.print_headline: Team Owned By Women Takes Partner, And a Stand
